					<h1>Prototyping &amp; User Testing</h1>

					<h3>Buying Items</h3>

					<p>Our intention in reducing wait times for check out was to collectively build up a list of items a shopper intended to buy. We thought about grocery items as (1) those with bar codes and (2) those without, like fruits and vegetables. We Wizard-of-Oz'd this interaction by asking participants to try scanning real-life items (like ramen) using the front and rear cameras on the tablet.</p>
				</div>

				<figure class="large-12 columns">
					<img src='images/smartcart/barcode.png' alt='Visual feedback when scanning a barcoded item' />
					<figcaption>Scanning a barcoded-item provides visual feedback once the scan is successful.</figcaption>
				</figure>

				<div class="medium-8 medium-centered columns">
					<p>Produce became tricky. One concept used computer vision to determine the color of produce, wifi to narrow the list to produce within range, and then prompted the user to select from a shortlist the correctly scanned item by swiping through. Although we mocked this up, we ended up not persuing this idea due to time and technology constraints.</p>


					<figure>
						<div class="slideshow" id="barcode-scanning">
							<div>
								<img src='images/smartcart/007.png' alt='Interface to choose from differen produce of the same color'>
							</div>
							<div>
								<img src='images/smartcart/008.png' alt='Interace to choose the correct produce'>
							</div>
							<div>
								<img src='images/smartcart/009.png' alt='Interface to confirm your selection'>
							</div>
						</div>
						<figcaption>In this produce-buying concept, the camera determines  the color of the produce, then wifi narrows the list down to a few items in range. Finally, the user confirms from a short list. Unfortunately, we did not persue this path.</figcaption>
					</figure>
				</div>

				<div class="medium-8 medium-centered columns">

					<p>Through user testing, we found that neither the front camera nor back camera was intuitive as a scanning mechanism. People also expressed worry about whether the camera was always on and always watching. We learned that lags created frustration, and lack of feedback in our Wizard of Oz demo was very confusing. For an action as critical as buying and scanning, it should be quick and reliable. More importantly, the purchasing decision should install a sense of confidence. 
					</p>

					<blockquote>
						Core actions, like scanning items should be quick, reliable, and instill confidence in the system.
					</blockquote>

					<p>We decided to try a handheld laser scanner. In our user testing, if we just left the barcode scanner by the tablet, people instinctively knew to pick it up and use it. Many of the problems we faced when using the camera (security, lag, awkwardness) did not exist.</p>

				</div>

