				<div class="medium-8 medium-centered columns">

					<h3>Checkout</h3>

					<p>Since all the items would be scanned and placed into the cart, we prototyped an Uber-like silent confirmation. You could simply leave the store with your cart – your credit card was charged, and everything would be complete. However, we were met by a lot of confusion by participants. Most surprising was that every single person expressed some sort of fear. </p>


					<blockquote>
					    People were afraid of being perceived as stealing things.
					</blockquote>

					<p>Causes of the fear ranged from buying by accident, not paying for the right items, or the fear of being perceived as stealing something. Such a behavioral change was unnatural, and SmartCart should ease users through the journey. In our redesign, we added explicit directions to an exit area of the store, and acted out a receipt verification employee to check whether people's shopping carts matched their transactions.</p>

					<h3>User Testing Methodology</h3>

					<p>Prior to user testing, we added a handful of items to our item database and hard-coded their approximate locations in the Menlo Park Safeway. We created a map that was similar to the Safeway. To simulate Wi-Fi localization, we set up a second tablet to control the cart's map position via Bluetooth. Following a general script for everyone, we asked participants to scan a list containing three predetermined items (window cleaner, almond milk, and orange juice), then halfway through the test, asked them to pick up something they had forgotten (croutons). In our debrief, we asked about usability issues and whether the system would be intimidating to use.</p>

				</div>
